      "type": "theory",
      "id": "theory_bin_frac",
      "title": "Binary Fractions",
      "content": "Just like decimal has a decimal point (3.14), binary has a **binary point** that separates whole numbers from fractions!\n\n**Fractional Place Values (powers of 2 with negative exponents):**\n\u2022 2\u207b\u00b9 = 1/2 = 0.5 (halves place)\n\u2022 2\u207b\u00b2 = 1/4 = 0.25 (quarters place)\n\u2022 2\u207b\u00b3 = 1/8 = 0.125 (eighths place)\n\u2022 2\u207b\u2074 = 1/16 = 0.0625 (sixteenths place)\n\n**Example 1: Convert 1.101 (binary) to decimal**\n\nBinary:    1   .  1     0     1\nPositions: 1   .  0.5   0.25  0.125\nCalculate: 1\u00d71    1\u00d70.5 0\u00d70.25 1\u00d70.125\nResults:   1  +  0.5 +  0   +  0.125 = 1.625\n\nSo 1.101 in binary = 1.625 in decimal!\n\n**Example 2: Convert 0.11 (binary) to decimal**\n\nBinary:    0.  1     1\nPositions:  .  0.5   0.25\nResults:    0.5 + 0.25 = 0.75\n\nSo 0.11 in binary = 0.75 in decimal!\n\n**Example 3: Convert 10.01 (binary) to decimal**\n\nWhole part: 10 (binary) = 2 (decimal)\nFractional: .01 (binary) = 0.25 (decimal)\nTotal: 2.25\n\n**Important Facts:**\n\u2022 Each position after the point is HALF the previous\n\u2022 Some decimal fractions can't be exactly represented in binary (like 0.1)\n\u2022 This is why computers sometimes have rounding errors!\n\u2022 Powers of 2 fractions (0.5, 0.25, 0.125, etc.) convert perfectly\n\n**Pro Tips:**\n\u2022 Handle whole and fractional parts separately\n\u2022 Remember: 0.1 (binary) = 0.5 (decimal)\n\u2022 Common pattern: 0.111... approaches 1.0"
    },
